<CaseStudy
  title="Agentic Data Analyst"
  description="An autonomous analyst agent that runs end-to-end statistical analysis on tabular data — a ReAct loop over a registry of statistical tests, sandboxed Python execution, and auto-generated reports. The analyst that never needs a brief."
  role="AI Systems Engineer"
  period="2025"
  stack={['ReAct', 'Claude Sonnet', 'FastAPI', 'Typer', 'Polars', 'Plotly', 'ChromaDB', 'Docker sandbox']}
  outcome="Full end-to-end statistical analysis in under 60s · sandboxed code execution · auto-generated reports with charts"
  codeUrl="https://github.com/Mprtham/Agentic-Data-Analyst"
>

  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>
    A data analyst's time is dominated by the repetitive middle layer of analytical work: load the data, check the distributions, run the appropriate statistical tests, generate visualisations, write it up. It's not creative — it's procedural. Could a ReAct agent with access to a registry of statistical tools handle this layer autonomously, freeing analysts to focus on interpretation and decision-making?
  </p>
  <p>
    The secondary constraint: code execution had to be sandboxed. Letting an LLM write and run arbitrary Python on a shared server is a security risk. The agent needed to run in an isolated container with no network access and resource limits.
  </p>

  <h2>The approach</h2>

  <h3>ReAct loop over a tool registry</h3>
  <p>
    The agent follows the ReAct (Reason + Act) pattern: it reasons about the data, selects the appropriate tool from a registry, executes it, observes the result, and reasons about what to do next. The tool registry includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Descriptive statistics (summary, distributions, outlier detection)</li>
    <li>Correlation analysis (Pearson, Spearman, point-biserial)</li>
    <li>Group comparison (t-test, ANOVA, Mann-Whitney U, Kruskal-Wallis)</li>
    <li>Categorical analysis (chi-square, Fisher's exact)</li>
    <li>Time series decomposition (trend, seasonality, stationarity)</li>
    <li>Visualisation (Plotly histograms, scatter plots, heatmaps, time series)</li>
    <li>Python execution (arbitrary Polars/pandas code in a sandbox)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The agent selects which tests to run based on the data types it detects — it won't run a t-test on a categorical variable. This type-aware routing reduces hallucination-driven errors significantly.
  </p>

  <h3>Sandboxed execution (Docker)</h3>
  <p>
    The Python execution tool runs code in a Docker container with no network access, 512MB memory limit, and a 30-second timeout. The container is spawned per execution and destroyed immediately after. Results (stdout, generated files) are passed back to the agent as observation context.
  </p>

  <h3>ChromaDB for context memory</h3>
  <p>
    Prior analysis results are embedded and stored in ChromaDB so the agent can retrieve relevant context across a session — if it ran a correlation analysis in step 2, it can reference those results when deciding which follow-up tests to run in step 6 without re-running them.
  </p>

